{
  "text": "To verify the inhibitory effect of adenosine on TRPML1 in the native environment, COS1 cells expressing GFP-TRPML1 were treated with 1 M vacuolin-1, a small chemical known to increase the size of lysosomes [CITATION_1] , for \u03fe10 h, and then the enlarged lysosomes were recorded under luminal-side-out mode with the pipette containing 10 M ML-SA1. TRPML1 currents in the luminal-side-out patch were markedly inhibited by bath application of adenosine (10 mM, pH 5.5) by 56.7 \u03ee 2.2% (Fig. 2, E and F) . These data suggest that luminal adenosine inhibits lysosomal TRPML1 channel activity. Reduced TRPML1-mediated Ca 2\u03e9 Release in ADA-deficient Cells-Next, we aimed to test whether adenosine accumulation inhibits TRPML1 in intact cells. TRPML1 activity in intact cells can be assessed by monitoring the cytoplasmic Ca 2\u03e9 change using a Fura-2-based Ca 2\u03e9 measurement. We compared ML-SA1-induced Fura-2 signals between WT and ADA \u03ea/\u03ea human fibroblasts. If adenosine accumulation inhibits TRPML1, we would expect to detect less Fura-2 signal in response to ML-SA1 in ADA \u03ea/\u03ea cells. As shown in Fig. 3 , A and C, ADA \u03ea/\u03ea cells exhibited a significantly smaller Fura-2 signal in response to ML-SA1 (50 M), decreasing from 0.0600 \u03ee 0.0052 in control fibroblasts to 0.0050 \u03ee 0.0008 in ADA \u03ea/\u03ea fibroblasts. This reduction in Fura-2 signal in ADA \u03ea/\u03ea cells was not caused by a decrease in lysosomal Ca 2\u03e9 content because ADA \u03ea/\u03ea cells showed a comparable Fura-2 signal in response to GPN (400 M), a cathepsin C substrate that induces osmotic lysis of lysosomes to release lysosomal Ca 2\u03e9 (Fig. 3D ). Interestingly, overexpression of ENT3 but not ENT3-G437R, a mutant ENT3 with compromised transport activity but normal subcellular localization [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , rescued the compromised Fura-2 response induced by ML-SA1 ( Fig. 3 , B and C) in ADA \u03ea/\u03ea fibroblasts without changing lysosomal Ca 2\u03e9 content ( Fig. 3D ).",
